TI Impact of POS data sharing on supply chain management: An experimental
   study
SO PRODUCTION AND OPERATIONS MANAGEMENT
VL 12
IS 1
BP 1
EP 11
PD SPR 2003
PY 2003
AB We examine the impact of point of sale (POS) data sharing on ordering
   decisions in a multi-echelon supply chain. In particular, we focus on
   how exposure to Pos data may help reduce the "bullwhip effect," the
   tendency of orders to increase in variability as one moves up a supply
   chain. Theoretical studies have shown that exposure to Pos data can lead
   to a reduction in the bullwhip effect when suppliers have no prior
   knowledge of the demand distribution. The benefit of sharing Pos data in
   stable industries, where the demand distribution is commonly known, is
   less clear. We study this phenomenon from a behavioral perspective in
   the context of a simple, serial, supply chain subject to information
   lags and stochastic demand. We find, using a controlled simulation
   experiment, that sharing Pos information does help reduce some
   components of the bullwhip effect in a stable demand setting, namely the
   order oscillation of upstream members. We offer one possible explanation
   for this improvement by examining the relationship between order
   decisions and demand line information.
