   results in reduced satisfaction levels leading to lower profits for the
   firm. We show that a salesperson selling products where the value of the
   upgrade is low prefers to make higher claims when the sales commission
   rate is sufficiently high. We conjecture that consumers aware of the
   incentive structure facing the salesperson expect the true value of the
   add-on feature to be lower than the claimed value. We study the optimal
   compensation scheme of a firm, which has to communicate her true type
   and retain its salesforce credibility. We identify the conditions under
   which a high-upgrade-type firm indicates its true value by altering
   sales commission rate and satisfaction-based commission rate.
