   untrustworthy and thus should have zero trust for others, is used to
   construct a null hypothesis. We test whether people are trusting or
   trustworthy and examine how inferring the intentions of those who trust
   affects trustworthiness. We also investigate the effect of stake on
   trust, and study the evolution of trust.
   Results show subjects exhibit some degree of trusting behavior, although
   a majority of them are not trustworthy and claim the entire social gain.
   Players are more reluctant to trust in later stages than in earlier ones
   and are more trustworthy if they are certain of the trustee's intention.
