   organizations prosper. Some firms, however, learn from their experience
   at a dramatic rate, while other firms exhibit very little learning at
   all. Three factors have been identified that affect the rate at which
   firms learn: (a) the proficiency of individual workers, (b) the ability
   of firm members to leverage knowledge accumulated by others, and (c) the
   capacity for coordinated activity inside the organization. Each factor
   varies with a particular kind of experience. An increase in cumulative
