   the market price of the product over time. Because anticipation of
   declining prices makes consumers less willing to invest in owning the
   durable good, selling can be self-defeating for the manufacturer. If the
   manufacturer instead leases the product, it can eliminate its own
   incentive to decrease the price over time, which allows it to extract
   larger rents from consumers. In this paper, we investigate how a durable
   goods manufacturer's choice between leasing and selling is affected by a
   complementary product that is produced by an independent firm. We show
